{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17412778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17412778"},"attributes":{"position":9,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12234"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513806"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:14:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:14:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12234"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261074"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:38:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:40:20+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":19,"questionsAnswered":7,"marksTotal":19,"marksAttainable":7,"marksAttempted":7,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T07:39:59+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.14,"questionsCorrect":1,"marksCorrect":1},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"12234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12234"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.02,0,0.12,0.82]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4756"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99015"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4756"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12234"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81408"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"147"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7560"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7572"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11857"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13881"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34008"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42716"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43305"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99015"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of worsening shortness of breath and audible wheeze. She has a history of mild episodes of breathlessness, especially in winter, for which she does not take any regular medications. She has not had an attack in over a year. She has type 1 diabetes for which she takes insulin. She does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly distressed. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 118/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 26/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. On auscultation, there are loud expiratory wheezes bilaterally. Her arterial blood gas analysis shows a pH of 7.5 (7.35-7.45), pCO2 27 mmHg (35-45) and pO2 64 mmHg (80-100).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV hydrocortisone","Intramuscular adrenaline","Subcutaneous benralizumab","Inhaled budesonide/formoterol","Nebulised salbutamol/ipratropium"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is experiencing an acute exacerbation of asthma, as evidenced by her sudden onset of dyspnoea, wheeze, tachypnoea, and characteristic arterial blood gas findings showing respiratory alkalosis (elevated pH, low pCO2) with hypoxaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENebulised salbutamol/ipratropium\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial management for an acute asthma exacerbation. Short-acting bronchodilators provide rapid relief of bronchospasm and should be administered first. The combination of salbutamol (a beta-2 agonist) and ipratropium (an anticholinergic) provides synergistic bronchodilation through different mechanisms. This patient has not yet received any treatment for her current exacerbation, making bronchodilators the logical first step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV hydrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E is an important component in the management of moderate to severe asthma exacerbations, but it is not the initial step. Systemic corticosteroids (either oral or intravenous) should be administered early in the course of treatment, typically after initiating bronchodilator therapy. They reduce airway inflammation and prevent relapse. This patient should receive systemic corticosteroids soon after the initial bronchodilator therapy is started.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular adrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily indicated for anaphylaxis, not for routine asthma exacerbations. Anaphylaxis typically presents with hypotension, urticaria, angioedema, and respiratory symptoms following exposure to an allergen. This patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with asthma rather than anaphylaxis, and her blood pressure is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubcutaneous benralizumab\u003C/strong\u003E is a biologic therapy that targets the interleukin-5 receptor, reducing eosinophilic inflammation in severe asthma. It is used as a maintenance therapy for severe eosinophilic asthma that is refractory to conventional treatments, not for acute exacerbations. It has a delayed onset of action and would not provide immediate relief in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhaled budesonide/formoterol\u003C/strong\u003E combines an inhaled corticosteroid with a long-acting beta-agonist. While this combination can be used in maintenance therapy and sometimes as part of a self-management plan for mild exacerbations at home, it is not the preferred initial treatment for an acute exacerbation in the Emergency Department.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Short-acting bronchodilators are the first-line therapy for acute asthma exacerbations.","Systemic corticosteroids should be administered early in moderate to severe asthma exacerbations.","Respiratory alkalosis with hypoxaemia is characteristic of an acute asthma exacerbation."],"references":["Cloutier MM, Dixon AE, Krishnan JA, Lemanske RF Jr, Pace W, Schatz M. Managing Asthma in Adolescents and Adults: 2020 Asthma Guideline Update From the National Asthma Education and Prevention Program. JAMA. 2020 Dec 8;324(22):2301-2317. doi: 10.1001/jama.2020.21974. PMID: 33270095.","Almadhoun K, Sharma S. Bronchodilators. 2021 Nov 21. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30085570."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81408"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12234"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/a